name: DJ's Bistro
featured_in: 17 Destination-Worthy Restaurants in Concord and Pleasant Hill
endorsement_copy: This unassuming restaurant, tucked away in a Concord mini-mall, has been a local fave for its hearty central European menu and large selection of German and Czech beer. This is your spot for Hungarian goulash, wiener schnitzel, and sauerbraten — all available to go, or to be enjoyed in the restaurant’s recently added canopy-covered outdoor dining area.

name: Fiola Mare
description: Fiola Mare celebrates Fabio Trabocchi's love for the life by the sea. This dreamwork is inspired by Italy’s coastlines and the bounty of its most pristine seafood. The Adriatic, Fabio's native coastline of Monte Conero, the world-renowned Amalfi Coast, Sicily, and Forte dei Marmi, are the inspiration of our menu experience featuring the finest crudos, seafood towers, delightful salads, handmade pasta, and our signature "Carrello del Pesce", a seafood cart featuring the daily best catch from Italy and all over the world is showcased at your table. Located in the chic and timeless Georgetown, Fiola Mare, with its unique, elegant, and nautical design, features wonderful scenic views of the waterfront and its marina. Its beautifully crafted cocktails and the superb wine list recognized with a Wine Spectator Best Award of Excellence. Known for its seen and be seen ambiance, Fiola Mare is home to Washington, D.C.’s best power lunch and offers exquisite private dining spaces for social and business events.In addition to the dining room, Fiola Mare features an extensive bar offering classic and modern cocktails as well as the full dining room menu. Fiola Mare welcomes walk ins. Valet parking is offered at the entrance to the restaurant.  To purchase Gift Cards, please visit https://www.fabiotrabocchi.com/shopCome to Fabio Trabocchi's elegant salute to Italian fish and shellfish preparations for the power crowd people-watching, the award-winning wine list, the breezy Georgetown waterfront atmosphere, and of course, Trabocchi's justly celebrated cooking, focused on fresh seafood sourced from three continents.
featured_in: D.C.’s Best Brunches
endorsement_copy: See and be seen brunching at Fiola Mare's swanky Georgetown waterfront location that just turned 10 in February. From 11:30 a.m. to 2:30 p.m. on weekends, expect classics such as lemon ricotta pancakes, tagliatelle carbonara, and decadent seafood towers along with seasonal a la carte dishes. A baller three-course “sparking brunch” option is more affordable than ever — down from $97 to $72 — and includes an appetizer, brunch favorites, dessert, a warm pastry, and bottomless bubbly or brunch cocktails, with a 75-minute time limit.

name: Scarpetta
description: The philosophy of Scarpetta’s kitchen is to create bold flavors by amplifying the essence of seasonal ingredients. The signature pastas are made in-house daily and are paired with the highest quality, locally sourced ingredients.  The understated-yet-elegant approach to design creates an environment that is simultaneously stylish, welcoming, and inspiring.
featured_in: Thanksgiving in Philly: Where to Dine Out

name: Fisherman's Cove
featured_in: The Best Bay Area Restaurants for Dungeness Crab Feasts
endorsement_copy: This tiny waterfront bait shop slash seafood shack is known for being one of the best spots in Bodega Bay for freshly shucked oysters — and, especially during the local crab season, for Dungeness, served in nachos, with wasabi cocktail sauce, and even as a sandwich on ciabatta with a choice of cocktail sauce or dill aioli. For the full experience, grab a seat at one of the picnic tables outside.

name: Via Locusta
description: Multiple parking garages between 17th & 18th on Chancellor St. & outdoor lot between 17th & 18th on Rittenhouse St.Walk-ins are welcome! IMPORTANT NOTE:Any reservation for Outside is weather dependent. We do not have a fully covered outdoor area and if there is inclement weather, we may have to cancel. Any reservation for Inside Dining Room is for indoor dining. We cannot move outside reservations inside. All indoor tables are reserved online and not held for walk-in guests.Rittenhouse has gained itself a pasta haven with the very pretty Via Locusta, where diners pluck porcini-filled agnolotti, while cooks in the overlooking kitchen create fresh pasta. Garganelli, paccheri, fazzoletti, and more shapes are handmade daily from locally sourced and freshly milled flour. If you’re unsure what pasta shape you’re committing to, the illustrated menu has you covered.
featured_in: Top Happy Hour Spots Opened Every Day in Philly
endorsement_copy: This Schulson Collective restaurant showcases Italian cuisine at its best, with a happy hour menu full of amazing antipasti (such as meatballs and focaccia), satisfying frittas (try the one with shrimp, calamari, and marinara), and outstanding drinks (featuring a selection of spritzes, cocktails, and wines). Happy hour here is every day from 4 p.m. to 6 p.m.

name: Oh! Calamares
description: Was very good . I had 2 glasses of 2009 Valencia [[HIGHLIGHT]]Spanish[[ENDHIGHLIGHT]] red and that was a perfect match...
featured_in: 25 Dishes for Offal Lovers Around NYC
endorsement_copy: Peruvian restaurants are almost always good for finding at least one organ meat: the cow heart kebabs known as anticuchos, which are often sold as street food back on home turf. At Oh! Calamares in Kearny, New Jersey, anticuchos are served on a sizzling platter with potatoes and boiled Peruvian corn. They’re flame-grilled and thus taste a bit smoky, and also pleasantly rubbery, considering they’re one of the body’s strongest muscles.

name: Itri Wood Fired Pizza Bar
description: Celebrating the rich Italian American culture of Bristol with a touch of 3rd generation irreverence, Itri offers unique and wood fired pizza, a full food menu, and craft cocktails! All reservations will have 90 minutes at their table to ensure service keeps flowing! Parties of 6+ will have 2 hours. If you are looking to dine longer, please contact the restaurant directly. Parties of 6+ must call the restaurant for reservations. Parties of 10+ must email events@itriwoodfired.com.

Ben.text: Great spot in Bristol, up and coming area. Easy parking, food was great, quick, will go back soon

Waters.text: Spectacular! Get there early to catch the Detroit.

Barbara.text: Always great food and service! One of my favorite local restaurants!

Michelle.text: The food is great!!  We had the fried mozzarella and buffalo chicken pizza, FANTASTIC!!  The drinks were great. The only thing is that the tables are close together and some of the people were very loud. It’s worth going to for the food. The town in Bristol is really beautiful too!!

parking_details: There is also a very large parking lot off of Mill Street.
private_party_facilities: We have an exclusive private room that can accommodate sit down dinners as well as stand-up cocktail parties. The space can hold up to 45 seated for a dinner and much more for a cocktail event. A great space for your shower, birthday party, anniversary, work party, etc. Please email events@itriwoodfired.com for more information.
featured_in: Bucks County’s Best Wings,
endorsement_copy: Wood-fired pizzas are a big draw at Itri Wood Fired in Bristol, but don’t sleep on the wings. This Mill Street restaurant offers outstanding wood-fired wings topped with sesame seeds and scallions and served with a buttermilk ranch dressing for dipping.

name: Pepe’s Cafe
featured_in: 13 Best Restaurants in Nevada City and Grass Valley
endorsement_copy: Pepe’s is a newer, solid destination for a nice big breakfast or a delicious lunch with a Mexican angle. For brunch, grab a mimosa and indulge in coconut-peach pancakes, and for lunch, go big with chimichangas — filled with chicken, beef, or pork — or grilled shrimp tacos. On a sunny day, it’s especially fun to sit at one of the outdoor tables and watch the town go by.

name: The Original Ghirardelli Ice Cream and Chocolate Shop
endorsement_copy: In a city with a rich chocolate history, Ghirardelli is the oldest continuously run chocolate factory in the United States. Lindt now owns it, so the chocolate is milky sweet, very smooth, and mass-produced. But a glossy hot fudge sundae is still a delight, and, even after its 2022 makeover, the Original Ghirardelli Ice Cream & Chocolate Shop is a classic San Francisco treat, billowing chocolate aroma onto historic brick-lined Ghirardelli Square.
lower_name: the original ghirardelli ice cream and chocolate shop
normalized_name: original ghirardelli ice cream  chocolate shop

name: Taishan Cuisine
description: I would definitely come back (maybe next time not at 2am) when I'm looking for a [[HIGHLIGHT]]cozy Chinese[[ENDHIGHLIGHT]] spot.

name: Kingdom of Dumpling
endorsement_copy: Don’t confuse this Noriega dumpling shop with its regally named rival, Shanghai Dumpling King, famous for its xiao long bao. Kingdom of Dumpling serves fine XLB, but it's really known for its wide array of Northern-style shui jiao dumplings, or boiled dumplings, with their thick hand-made wrappers, and fillings like pork and napa cabbage or shrimp with chives. Pro tip: Score bags of frozen dumplings to take home and steam up at your leisure.

name: Tamarine Restaurant Amp Gallery
featured_in: 18 Best Places to Eat and Drink in Palo Alto
endorsement_copy: This modern Vietnamese restaurant at the top end of University Avenue has been serving shaking beef, lemongrass sea bass, and seared miso duck since 2002. Owned by two sisters, the space is also a rotating art gallery and a power spot for cocktails.

name: Market Street
featured_in: 'BucksWire Exclusive: Clover Locations Revealed

name: Benders Bar Amp Grill
featured_in: 15 Best Dog-Friendly Bars and Restaurants in San Francisco
endorsement_copy: Bender's is a legit neighborhood dive bar with stiff drinks, two pool tables, ample bicycle "parking," a back patio, heavy metal on the jukebox, and some of the wildest “totzz” and hard shell tacos in town. Even better: You can totally bring your dog there and house-made dog treats are available for purchase so Fifi doesn't get too jealous of your food.

name: Fish.
endorsement_copy: Fish. is a little off the beaten ferry path, but getting there is worth the effort. It's all about sustainable seafood, including a raw seafood market for locals. Check the chalkboard for the daily catch, order at the counter, and sit at an outdoor picnic table beside the harbor to enjoy a generous portion of whatever’s fresh. In season, the Dungeness crab roll should catch your attention.

name: Burma！Burma！
featured_in: Here’s Where to Eat Around Dublin, Pleasanton, and Livermore
endorsement_copy: This Burmese restaurant is a favorite in the Tri-Valley area, serving popular dishes such tea leaf and rainbow salads, and pumpkin shrimp curry. Those who live a gluten-free lifestyle will be relieved to know that many of the dishes are sans gluten and clearly labeled on the menu.

name: Halal Wings Plus
featured_in: The Best, Crispiest Wings in San Francisco
endorsement_copy: Tenderloin spot Halal Wings Plus boasts wings that are indeed halal. They’re small but flavor-packed and come in varieties like spicy mango habanero, barbecue, and garlic Parmesan. These guys also do fun mashup items like Boom Boom Fries, which come topped with fried chicken, jalapeños, and a house sauce.

name: New Woey Loy Goey Restaurant
featured_in: The Best Places to Eat and Drink in San Francisco’s Chinatown
endorsement_copy: This Chinatown basement restaurant — whose history goes back some 90 years — serves some of the heartiest and most inexpensive Cantonese food in town. Customer favorites include old-school dishes like tomato-and-beef chow mein, salt-and-pepper fried pork chops, and steamed pork hash. The rice plates are an especially good deal, at just $9 or $10 a pop.

name: Fats Asia Bistro, Roseville
featured_in: Everywhere Worth Eating Between San Francisco and Lake Tahoe
endorsement_copy: In 1939, Frank Fat started wok frying deliciousness in downtown Sacramento, and the hits haven’t stopped coming: Fat went on to open a few restaurants and dim sum bars in his time, in Folsom and Roseville, too. The red chili tiger prawns are tough to beat, and dumplings are a surefire way to have a good time — very road trip friendly, too.

name: Fish
featured_in: The Best Bay Area Restaurants for Dungeness Crab Feasts
endorsement_copy: Fish is known for responsibly sourcing seafood from trusted fishermen. The combined market and restaurant sits right on the bay in Sausalito, and the generous outdoor space boasts fresh views. Fans love the Dungeness crab roll, a torpedo-shaped bun stuffed to the gills with lump meat, as well as the Louie salad.

name: PPQ Dungeness Island
featured_in: Double Trouble: 11 San Francisco Dishes and Menus For Two
endorsement_copy: When Dungeness is in season, couples can be seen digging in gleefully to the $60 dinner-for-two special at PPQ, which includes imperial rolls, chicken-cabbage salad, and garlic noodles in addition to a whole roasted crab. They even throw in fried bananas with ice cream for dessert.

name: Wooly Pig
description: The [[HIGHLIGHT]]coffee[[ENDHIGHLIGHT]] was good and the croissant was very nice; light and flaky.
featured_in: Where to Eat and Drink in Dogpatch

name: Durty Nelly's
featured_in: 15 Lively Irish Pubs to Grab a Pint in San Francisco
endorsement_copy: Cozy up to Irish stew and a glass of whiskey by the real fireplace while the Sunset District weather — typically cold and foggy — provides the believably Irish atmosphere outdoors. Durty Nelly’s also qualifies as a dive bar/sports bar, with requisite trivia nights and karaoke.

name: The Chieftain Irish Pub Amp Restaurant
featured_in: 15 Lively Irish Pubs to Grab a Pint in San Francisco
endorsement_copy: The lively atmosphere and occasional live band are part of the draw of this SoMa bar. Lunch and dinner menus include tacos, nachos, and even a plant-based burger, but the best bet is the Irish fare like the classic Irish breakfast — dubbed the Chieftain Irish Grill here  — of fried eggs, sausage, bacon, black and white pudding, grilled tomato, baked beans, and chips.

name: Tadaima
description: go comfort food spot in the Mission. Sister to the Okaeri Japanese [[HIGHLIGHT]]sushi restaurant[[ENDHIGHLIGHT]] just next door!
featured_in: San Francisco’s Hottest New Restaurants, January 2025

name: The Bitter End
description: And it has a great [[HIGHLIGHT]]happy hour special[[ENDHIGHLIGHT]]! It's a great dive bar for any occasion.
featured_in: 15 Lively Irish Pubs to Grab a Pint in San Francisco

name: La Mexicana Bakery
featured_in: The 17 Best Bakeries in San Francisco
endorsement_copy: In the heart of the Mission at 24th Street and York, this Mexican bakery is known for its rich and eggy pan dulce — shaped as seashells, turtles, alligators, and wiggling worms — as well as its Salvadoran sesame seed cake. It’s cash only, but less than 10 bucks will buy a tray of half a dozen sweet treats.

name: Lunette
description: Ordering all those dishes though, the portions were not that big for [[HIGHLIGHT]]2 people[[ENDHIGHLIGHT]] (we definitely felt we...
featured_in: The 12 Best Places to Eat and Drink on the Embarcadero

name: Wong Lee Bakery
featured_in: The Best Places to Eat and Drink in San Francisco’s Chinatown
endorsement_copy: Chinatown’s most legendary egg tarts can be found at Golden Gate Bakery, but in a pinch you can get your fix at Wong Lee Bakery, an itty bitty counter on Jackson Street. The egg tarts are everything you could want and more with a flaky crust — no soggy bottoms — and a smooth custard inside. There’s also a selection of dim sum classics including dumplings, noodles, and more.

name: New Woey Loy Goey Restaurant
featured_in: The Best Places to Eat and Drink in San Francisco’s Chinatown
endorsement_copy: This Chinatown basement restaurant — whose history goes back some 90 years — serves some of the heartiest and most inexpensive Cantonese food in town. Customer favorites include old-school dishes like tomato-and-beef chow mein, salt-and-pepper fried pork chops, and steamed pork hash. The rice plates are an especially good deal, at just $9 or $10 a pop.

name: Grass Valley Pasty Co.
featured_in: 13 Best Restaurants in Nevada City and Grass Valley
endorsement_copy: During the Gold Rush, Grass Valley was home to many migrants from Cornwall, England, and the Pasty Co. keeps that bit of history alive with a selection of authentic, flaky, Cornish pasties — savory, half-moon-shaped hand pies, made freshly daily. Options are limited, but there are rotating vegetarian and meat-filled selections to choose from. If you see a barbacoa beef option on the menu, get it without hesitation.

name: Grass Valley Brewing Company
featured_in: 13 Best Restaurants in Nevada City and Grass Valley
endorsement_copy: Grass Valley Brewing Co. does brewery food just right — snacks include garlic fries and spicy wings, plus there’s a full menu of burgers and sandwiches ranging from the healthful to the decadent. While there, sample the brewery’s hazy IPAs, stouts, and dark Mexican lager — and pick up some canned beers to take home.

name: Brazen Head
description: Cool NYC neighborhood steakhouse vibe. Very crowded for a [[HIGHLIGHT]]Sunday night[[ENDHIGHLIGHT]], but got a seat at the bar...

top_reviews.text: We've been coming to the Brazen Head for the last 30 years. A bunch of us bartenders from Reno always made this our favorite spot. I'll be there next week...
During a visit to San Francisco, we found Brazen Head, an Irish pub with a French menu, in Cow Hollow--located west of Wharf and east of the Presidio -...
Finally able to come here after many years of hearing about this restaurant. My buddy and I both ordered their signature prime rib and ceasar salad. I asked...

featured_in: 12 Restaurants Perfect for a Solo Meal in San Francisco, The 14 Best Steakhouses in San Francisco

name: Krampus’ Cove at Rye
featured_in: The Best Holiday Bars and Restaurants Pop-Ups in San Francisco
endorsement_copy: If you prefer a holiday bar pop-up with a darker edge to it, Rye is spinning the Krampus myth into its theme for the month with Krampus’ Cove. Expect less of the Mariah Carey-style holiday spirit and more of the vibe of goth Christmas trees decorated with skeletons, doll heads, and severed body parts (faux, of course). Expect strong, themed drinks like Red Snow, a drink made with vodka, coconut-peppermint syrup, absinthe, and sherry. Festivities kick off on Monday, December 9, through Tuesday, December 31.

name: Imperial Garden Seafood Restaurant
featured_in: The 14 Best San Francisco Restaurants Open on Christmas Day
endorsement_copy: As this classic Bayview Chinese restaurant ramps up its offerings — including vegan dim sum — the San Bruno Avenue restaurant will keep its doors open on Christmas like it’s any other day. Open since 1995, fans keep coming back for rich siu mai and seafood congee.

name: Happy Donuts
featured_in: 13 Gloriously Golden Doughnut Shops in San Francisco
endorsement_copy: It’s hard not to be happy when eating a doughnut, especially if it’s a raised glazed from Happy Donuts. Open 24 hours a day, Happy Donuts is a traditional shop that serves the melt-in-your mouth classics you remember from childhood.

name: Fayes
featured_in: 9 Spicy and Creamy Chais to Keep You Cozy in San Francisco
endorsement_copy: There’s Tartine on 18th Street, sure, but what Tartine has in bread, its neighbor Fayes across the street has in drinks. That includes San Francisco’s only remaining $1 coffee, but also a spicy chai that is well-worth trying. The shop uses David Rio, if that’s any indication of where else to try.

name: Lung Fung Bakery
featured_in: Where to Eat and Drink in the Richmond District
endorsement_copy: The signboard menu at this old-school Cantonese bakery, with prices given in cents instead of dollars, is a throwback to a different era. You won’t find anything resembling an entree here, but the egg custard tarts are the flakiest in the neighborhood, and the meaty baked barbecue pork buns are probably tops in the entire city. Dragon Beaux is another favorite in the area for dim sum.

name: David Rio Chai Bar
featured_in: 9 Spicy and Creamy Chais to Keep You Cozy in San Francisco
endorsement_copy: People are more or less familiar with the animal-themed works of David Rio, including its spacious Market Street cafe. The beautiful thing about grabbing chai at this Civic Center shop is the variety: there are 10 different chai lattes on the menu, including the spicy Cub Chai. That bad boy, when made with macadamia milk, may be the greatest chai latte in the city.

name: The Jingle Bar At Swiss Louis
featured_in: The Best Holiday Bars and Restaurants Pop-Ups in San Francisco
endorsement_copy: Roving pop-up the Jingle Bar is setting up shop at Swiss Louis Italian & Seafood Restaurant for the holiday season, promising festive decor like twinkling trees and plenty of tinsel, a soundtrack of nonstop holiday hits, games, and festive themed cocktails and bar snacks. Tickets are limited, so get them ahead of time online.
lower_name: the jingle bar at swiss louis

name: Hakka Restaurant 客家山莊
featured_in: The 16 Best Chinese Restaurants in San Francisco
endorsement_copy: Often described as a kind of soulful cousin to Cantonese food, the cuisine of China’s migratory Hakka people abounds with pickled vegetables and slow-cooked meats. This homey Outer Richmond restaurant is one of the few places in San Francisco to get hooked on its rustic, comforting flavors. Must-order dishes include salt-baked chicken, clams stir-fried with basil, and braised pork belly with shrimp paste — all of which come in family-style portions, so be sure to come hungry or with a group.

name: Manitas Cafe
featured_in: San Francisco’s Best Restaurants For Solid Weekday Breakfasts
endorsement_copy: Manitas’ owners promise recipes “stolen from Grandma” — that is if your grandma made blisteringly spicy chilaquiles and breakfast burritos with chorizo, eggs, and potato. Best of all, breakfast is served all day long.

name: Java On Ocean
featured_in: 17 Best San Francisco Coffee Shops
endorsement_copy: Ocean Avenue plays host to lots of fantastic restaurants and bars, but few destinations are as open, enormous, and affordable as Java on Ocean. The shop features tons of specialty drinks, and not specialty coffee, mind you, but items like rose, lavender, and zebra lattes.

name: Grand Coffee
featured_in: 17 Destination Restaurants, Bars, and Bakeries in the Mission District, 17 Best San Francisco Coffee Shops
endorsement_copy: Nabeel Slimi grew up between the Bay Area and Palestine and, after the Great Recession, found a way to create a space for all of that richness — plus everyone else out there with a similar complexity. The coffee is tasty, with the familiar milk chocolate notes of a solid light roast anyone on Mission Street would be delighted to find.

name: Abanico Coffee Roasters
description: Abanico has a rich [[HIGHLIGHT]]coffee[[ENDHIGHLIGHT]]/tea menu, and the space itself has comfy seating and tables- a great spot...
featured_in: 17 Best San Francisco Coffee Shops

name: Java on Ocean
featured_in: 17 Best San Francisco Coffee Shops
endorsement_copy: Ocean Avenue plays host to lots of fantastic restaurants and bars, but few destinations are as open, enormous, and affordable as Java on Ocean. The shop features tons of specialty drinks, and not specialty coffee, mind you, but items like rose, lavender, and zebra lattes.

name: Miette Patisserie
featured_in: 16 Best Cakes in San Francisco
endorsement_copy: With sweet shops both in Hayes Valley and in the Ferry Building, Miette is there for when your sweet tooth strikes. Miette makes some of the prettiest cakes in town, perfectly smooth, in pastel colors, with a single rose or cherry nestled on top. The tomboys are the top sellers, with dark chocolate layers, and luscious Italian buttercream.

name: Pomet
featured_in: All the Michelin Star Restaurants in the Bay Area, Mapped
endorsement_copy: Pomet is the epitome of the farm-to-table ethos, as it’s run by Aomboon Deasy, one of the owners of K&J Orchards. (Green Star)

name: House of Tadu Ethiopian Kitchen
featured_in: 12 Best Restaurants and Bars in Mission Bay
endorsement_copy: This family-run business is one of the few Ethiopian restaurants in San Francisco proper, first opened in the Tenderloin, and now with a second location in Mission Bay. Expect spongy flatbread, thick stews, and lamb tibs tossed with berbere and chiles.

name: For The Record
featured_in: The 14 Best Places to Eat and Drink in the Marina
endorsement_copy: In our modern world, sometimes what one needs is a blast from the past — and For the Record has that in spades. The retro- and 70s-themed bar features fun (and funky) decor alongside a menu of solid cocktails that is updated often with new drinks. If you’re in more of a sampling mood, there are Cheekies, the bar’s name for mini cocktail-esque shots that’ll taste much better than those shots you did in college.

name: DH Noodles
featured_in: The 25 Best South Bay Area Restaurants
endorsement_copy: DH Noodles specializes in northwestern Chinese cuisine. Start your meal with braised meat tucked between flatbread or wrapped in a scallion pancake. Order the signature Lanzhou beef noodles, which are served in a light broth with a nutty chili oil. The stars of the show are aromatic dishes such as cumin lamb fried noodles, spicy lamb chops, and chicken tossed in a Sichuan sauce.

name: Beth Marie's Old Fashioned Ice Cream
featured_in: 14  Delectable Dallas Ice Cream Shops, The 17 Best Ice Cream Shops in San Francisco
endorsement_copy: Beth Marie’s mouth-watering flavors, such as Turtle Torture with caramel cups, chocolate pecans, and caramel swirl; Texas honey whiskey; and butter pecan, will inspire a taste for more.
lower_name: beth marie's old fashioned ice cream
normalized_name: beth maries old fashioned ice cream

name: Milkbomb Ice Cream
featured_in: The 17 Best Ice Cream Shops in San Francisco
endorsement_copy: If ice cream is a dessert that already makes you weak in the knees, Milkbomb will give you more ways to enjoy the treat. From unique flavors like Fruity Pebbles, White Rabbit, or mangonada — made of mango puree, chamoy, and Tajin — there’s also the added appeal of sandwiching those flavors inside a doughnut.

name: Nieves de Cinco de Mayo
featured_in: UPDATED: Where to Eat Shaved Ice, Italian Ice, & Snow Cones
endorsement_copy: Unfortunately, their location in the Mission Market was lost in the fire that destroyed several homes and businesses. However, they're back, offering raspado, or Mexican shaved ice, in flavors like mango with chili powder, strawberry-lime, or guava. The Latino ice-creamery is an extension of a popular mini-chain in San Jose and Oakland.

name: What's The Scoop
featured_in: 14 Destination Restaurants in Bayview and Hunter’s Point, The 17 Best Ice Cream Shops in San Francisco
endorsement_copy: With more than 40 flavors, What’s the Scoop, the neighborhood’s only ice cream shop, opened in November 2022 from music lover Anthony Womack. The parlor carries E-40’s Goon With The Spoon ice cream brand, but Womack also makes his own creations including a Frank Ocean nod called Channel Oreo.

name: Simple Pleasures Cafe
featured_in: 15 Best Dog-Friendly Bars and Restaurants in San Francisco
endorsement_copy: In the Outer Richmond Simple Pleasures Cafe keeps large parties buzzing with a big parklet suited for groups of any size — including any amount of animals. The neighborhood institution has served the city since 1978 and, while it’s well-lit parklet is much newer, longtime residents need no instruction to get their morning fix on Balboa Street.

name: Lemat
featured_in: The 16 Best Restaurants in Berkeley
endorsement_copy: This homey, family-run Ethiopian restaurant in South Berkeley is known for its tender, buttery kitfo (a traditional raw beef dish); its tangy, all-teff injera; and its flavorful veggie combo spread.

name: Cielito Lindo
featured_in: 19 Bay Area Spots Where You Can Find Crispy, Cheesy Quesabirria Tacos, The 13 Best Lunch Spots Across San Francisco
endorsement_copy: Perhaps the only spot where you can routinely snag quesabirria on the west side of the city, Cielito Lindo brings some much-needed regional variety to the neighborhood, serving pambazos and a wide variety of tortas in addition to its headlining quesabirria — a notably crisp and juicy version.

name: Chuck’s Takeaway
featured_in: The 13 Best Lunch Spots Across San Francisco
endorsement_copy: Chef Charles Phan’s casual sandwich counter in the Mission goes all in on an array of sandwiches. The CP OG #3 is the chef’s take on a classic banh mi built on a baked-in-house baguette using the chef’s pate and pickles. It’s essentially a takeout-only situation but these handhelds make a perfect park lunch.

name: Dinosaurs
featured_in: The 13 Best Lunch Spots Across San Francisco
endorsement_copy: The Ocean Avenue location of mini-chain Dinosaurs makes for a great grab-and-go lunch option, with affordable Vietnamese iced coffee, avocado milkshakes, spring rolls, and a good-sized banh mi stuffed with shaking beef, lemongrass pork, or spicy tuna.

name: The Bird
featured_in: The 13 Best Eating and Drinking Destinations in SoMa
endorsement_copy: The Bird offers fried chicken sandwiches with pickles and a brightly acidic slaw. Add a beer and curly fries to make it a happier meal, and try the apple fritters if you have extra room in your stomach.

name: Uncle Boy's
featured_in: The 17 Best Restaurants Around Golden Gate Park
endorsement_copy: Got a game night to head to? Need a juice-dripping, cost-saving burger that’s as San Francisco as it gets? Uncle Boy’s is the Golden Gate Park-adjacent answer for any get-togethers. The O.G. Burger is just $8.50, full of wagyu beef and all the classic fixings.

name: Bubbala's
featured_in: The Best Places to Get Jewish Food for the High Holidays in the Bay Area
endorsement_copy: Bubbala’s in San Anselmo hasn’t technically opened yet, as of September 17, but that hasn’t stopped the upcoming restaurant from creating a holiday menu perfect for takeout. Nosh on Aunt Harriet’s brisket, marinated Chicken Marbella, pan-roasted chicken, or roasted stuffed eggplant; each item is available a la carte or as part of a dinner that feeds 4 to 5 people and comes with two sides, round raisin challah, and an apple galette. “Break-fast” items will also be available, such as a bagel and schmear box or platter. Orders for Rosh Hashanah are available for pickup between Tuesday, October 1, and Thursday, October 3; Yom Kippur orders can be picked up on Friday, October 11.

name: Joella's Deli
featured_in: The 18 Best Destination Restaurants in Napa Valley
endorsement_copy: San Francisco Chronicle associate food critic Cesar Hernandez heaped plenty of praise on Joella’s, particularly for its spicy fried chicken, which can be enjoyed on a sandwich or in nugget form. Aside from the chicken, the menu offers a Buffalo chicken Caesar wrap, fried pickles, and PB&J bread pudding. Orders can be placed online for pick up at the food truck, which has a couple of tables available for customers.

name: Tacos el Muchacho Alegre
featured_in: The 18 Best Destination Restaurants in Napa Valley
endorsement_copy: Napa’s destination restaurants aren’t just of the fine dining variety, just ask Rancho Gordo founder Steve Sando, who’s intimately familiar with wine country’s best taco trucks. You’ll find El Muchacho Alegre tucked alongside the Universal Auto repair shop and the move is to order the torta ahogada, a Jaliscian specialty. The meat-filled sandwich is almost like a fiery French dip, served with a gazpacho-like salsa and drenched in a savory tomato and chile sauce.

name: robberbaron
featured_in: 19 Exciting Wine Bars in San Francisco
endorsement_copy: If you want a wine bar that’s not too “wine bar,” and feels more casual and fun, Robberbaron is the neighborhood place to go. The wine menu skews toward European and California options, with fun descriptors to tempt visitors into ordering (A recent gem: “Bad Bunny likes it”).

name: Andina
description: We loved it. Order at the front and they bring the food to you pretty darn fast We had the bowl, chicken and beef empanadas (excellent) and the vegan…
featured_in: Where to Find the Best Food and Drink Around Hayes Valley

name: Roaming Goat
description: We enjoyed our [[HIGHLIGHT]]brunch[[ENDHIGHLIGHT]] here and we had excellent service from our waiter, Alex.
featured_in: 19 Exciting Wine Bars in San Francisco

name: Focaccia At Liguria Bakery
featured_in: The 20 Best Dishes and Drinks of San Francisco
endorsement_copy: It's hard to explain what strange alchemy goes into Liguria's focaccia, but it might be magic. In any case, it certainly compels people to get up early and stand in line for a slice or two before they sell out, and has since 1911. Eat your pizza focaccia warm from the bag, or head down the street to equally historic Mario's Bohemian Cigar Store to enjoy it in an oven-baked meatball sandwich.

name: Protege
featured_in: All the Michelin Star Restaurants in the Bay Area, Mapped
endorsement_copy: Two French Laundry grads, a chef and a somm, delight with a more relaxed seven-course tasting menu in Palo Alto. (1 star)

name: Shalimar Restaurant
featured_in: 20 Destination Restaurants and Bars in the Tenderloin, The 13 Restaurants in San Francisco Changing the Narrative for Gluten-Free Diners
endorsement_copy: This Indian restaurant has a cult following for a reason — Shalimar is putting out some of the most reliably tasty food in the city, like succulent chicken tandoori; spicy, saucy okra; and destination-worthy goat karahi. The freshly-made naan is also a must, and the biryanis are well worth an order, too.

name: House hot chocolate at Dandelion Chocolate
endorsement_copy: Dandelion Chocolate changed the game on bean to bar in San Francisco, and the hot chocolate is a great way to taste what makes the company so popular. It’s an uber rich treat made with  70 percent Camino Verde, Ecuador single-origin chocolate and perfect for sipping as you walk around the city.
lower_name: house hot chocolate at dandelion chocolate

name: Sai Jai Thai
endorsement_copy: Venture to this humble restaurant in the Tenderloin, allegedly a favorite of movie star Keanu Reeves, for classic and unabashedly spicy Thai cuisine. Per the San Francisco Chronicle, the most famous dish on the menu is the barbecue pork shoulder, which gets coated in a fish sauce marinade before being grilled.

name: Manna
featured_in: 14 Bold Korean Restaurants in San Francisco
endorsement_copy: Inner Sunset residents turn to this Irving Street corner restaurant for its solid and extensive selection of Korean food — everything from spicy seafood stew to kimchi pancakes. You’ll likely see lots of diners digging into some variety of bibimbap, with the crispy rice buried under beef, vegetables, seafood, or a combo of all three.

name: Khan Toke Thai House
featured_in: 20 Classic Restaurants Every San Franciscan Must Try
endorsement_copy: Open since 1976, Khan Toke says that it’s one of San Francisco’s first Thai restaurants. It’s also one of the city’s fanciest, as diners are required to remove their shoes before they’re led to low, hand-carved tables. The menu’s got over 100 items, so savvy diners ask the white-jacketed waiters “what’s good tonight?” to make sure they get the kitchen’s best and brightest.

name: Locanda Wine Bar
endorsement_copy: If you’re looking to extensively explore Italian wines alongside a selection of classic Italian antipasti, Locanda Wine Bar is more than willing to oblige. Get a selection of meats and cheese, while drinking a glass of rosé or pinot grigio of your choice (or whatever else you’re feeling at the moment). There are special events to attend, such as wine dinners and live music nights, plus a cocktail menu for those who perhaps aren’t as enthusiastic about wine.

name: Banter Wine
endorsement_copy: The El Cerrito community welcomed this new wine bar with open arms, but it’s attracted a crowd beyond the modest city’s borders. Expect wines from France, Italy, Spain, Mexico, and South Africa, skewing toward sustainable, organic, biodynamically produced wines from smaller wineries. Banter offers bites during the week, but they also collaborate with exciting pop-ups such as Chino Latino pop-up Tacos Sincero and more.

name: Riggers Loft Wine Company R Amp B Cellars
endorsement_copy: Both tasting room and wine bar, Riggers Loft offers tasty pours with unbeatable bay views. The tasting room for R&B Cellars, Riggers Loft also regularly features wines from Carica Wines, Wachira Wines, Prima Materia, and more. There is a menu of Limited Reserve and Library Wines, and they also offer ciders from Far West Cider Company (for any wine-averse tag-alongs).

name: Bay Grape
endorsement_copy: Couple Josiah Baldivino and Stevie Stacionis started this Oakland wine shop and bar in 2014, serving wines and small plates in a comfortable setting. If you’re intimidated by wines, the shop offers tastings on Saturdays, and blind tastings on Sundays, if you’re really looking to dig deeper into the various styles.

name: Ain't Normal Cafe
featured_in: The Best East Bay Coffee Shops With Free Wi-Fi
endorsement_copy: Sure, when you’re looking for a place to work from, wi-fi is the major draw, but coffee fans will appreciate the excellent offerings at Ain’t Normal Cafe — wi-fi aside. The food is also a draw in its own right; San Francisco Chronicle associate food critic Cesar Hernandez praised the shop’s menu, writing that its “simple, punched-up dishes ... routinely impress.”

name: Cafe Alma
featured_in: 14 Ultra-Fresh Salads in San Francisco
endorsement_copy: This cafe is a here-today-gone-tomorrow kind of operation, meaning that someday the space will be closed when the building inevitably gets redeveloped. In the meantime, community groups like the San Francisco Clayer’s Club rely on the cafe for its four affordable salads. The Romaine Wedge is a must-try, starring Point Reyes blue cheese and big hunks of bacon dressing.

name: Parker Potrero
description: The line at plow was a little ridiculous but I still wanted an awesome breakfast. Luckily Parker always hits the spot. French toast for the sweet side…
featured_in: 14 Ultra-Fresh Salads in San Francisco, Where to Eat and Drink in Potrero Hill

name: Cholita Linda
featured_in: 18 Excellent and Child-Friendly Restaurants in the East Bay
endorsement_copy: From an always-busy farmers market food truck in 2008 to three brick-and-mortars (in Oakland, Alameda, and San Francisco), this pan-Latin spot highlights Peruvian, Mexican, and Cuban flavors and is a great place for a tot’s first meal out. Cholita Linda reliably delivers for families: Highchairs available; noise level moderate; aguas frescas flowing; and the combo of sweet plantains, rice, and black beans, all naturally appealing to kids. Fish tacos can be ordered plain, too, while adults revel in carnitas tacos, Cubano sandwiches, and the sweet-tangy-savory picadillo, which marries ground beef, olives, raisins, and peppers in one powerhouse dish.

name: Oceanview Diner
featured_in: 13 Cooperatively-Owned Restaurants, Bakeries, and Markets in the Bay Area
endorsement_copy: The nearly 40-year-old diner in West Berkeley known as Bette’s Oceanview has a storied history, known for fluffy pancakes and takeout pizza from the to-go counter. In recent times, the family-run business decided to close. However, to the delight of many patrons, workers banded together and recently reopened it under the new name, Oceanview Diner — and as a cooperatively-run business. The menu remains the same.

name: Pineapples
featured_in: The 9 Best Places to Find Hawai‘i Food in the Bay Area
endorsement_copy: Head to Pineapples for the most refreshing taste of the islands: A mountain of wispy, Hawaiian-style shave ice available in tropical flavors like lilikoi, pineapple, and mango. Order a scoop of vanilla ice cream tucked inside and load it up with mochi, shaved coconut, and, most importantly, a snow cap of condensed milk.

name: Sequoia Diner
featured_in: The 14 Best Spots for Brunch in the East Bay
endorsement_copy: This chic Laurel District diner is open for breakfast, lunch, and weekend brunch, Wednesday through Sunday. The waffles and biscuits are spectacular, as are the breakfast sandwiches, and there are plenty of vegetarian-friendly options — and bloody marys and Irish coffees to boot.

name: Sequoia Diner
featured_in: The 14 Best Spots for Brunch in the East Bay
endorsement_copy: This chic Laurel District diner is open for breakfast, lunch, and weekend brunch, Wednesday through Sunday. The waffles and biscuits are spectacular, as are the breakfast sandwiches, and there are plenty of vegetarian-friendly options — and bloody marys and Irish coffees to boot.

name: Smitty's Lounge
featured_in: Here Are the Hottest New Bars in the East Bay
endorsement_copy: New ownership took over Smitty’s Lounge and reopened the dive bar in March 2024, just in time for (what is believed to be) the bar’s 100th anniversary. Owners JJ Jenkins and Shari Murphy gave the interior a “subtly refreshed interior,” per East Bay Nosh, so expect much of the same divey charm as before.

name: Ruby Room
featured_in: Here Are the Hottest New Bars in the East Bay
endorsement_copy: Ruby Room was a 25-year staple of Oakland that was forced to shutter in December 2023, but thanks to the husband-and-wife team behind restaurant Blue Nile, Ruby Room is back. Music events continue on, with a mix of hip hop, jazz and funk, and classics.

name: Happy Bakery
featured_in: Where to Eat in the Sunset and Parkside
endorsement_copy: Happy Bakery’s fried taro dumpling is perhaps as indulgent a treat as one can eat on Irving Street. Cars double-park up and down the blocks running from 20th to 25th Avenue to let a passenger out for a mad dash to the tiny outlet. For less than $10, Happy Bakery provides a feast. Be warned, however, that this spot is cash only.
